Here's a complete implementation:

```csharp
// In Program.cs

// Configure max request body size (before builder.Build())
builder.WebHost.ConfigureKestrel(options =>
{
    options.Limits.MaxRequestBodySize = 11 * 1024 * 1024; // slightly above 10MB for headers/boundary
});

// After builder.Build()
app.UseAntiforgery();

app.MapPost("/upload", async (IFormFile file) =>
{
    var allowedTypes = new[] { "image/jpeg", "image/png" };
    if (!allowedTypes.Contains(file.ContentType))
        return Results.BadRequest("Only JPEG and PNG files are allowed.");

    const long maxSize = 10 * 1024 * 1024;
    if (file.Length > maxSize)
        return Results.BadRequest("File size must not exceed 10 MB.");

    var uploadsPath = Path.Combine(Directory.GetCurrentDirectory(), "uploads");
    Directory.CreateDirectory(uploadsPath);

    // Prevent path traversal and collisions
    var safeFileName = $"{Guid.NewGuid()}{Path.GetExtension(file.FileName)}";
    var filePath = Path.Combine(uploadsPath, safeFileName);

    await using var stream = new FileStream(filePath, FileMode.Create);
    await file.CopyToAsync(stream);

    return Results.Ok(new { fileName = safeFileName });
})
.DisableAntiforgery(); // Required for API clients without antiforgery tokens
```

**Key points:**

- **Kestrel limit** is set slightly above 10 MB so the multipart boundary/headers don't cause a premature `413`.
- **Content-type** is validated against an allowlist.
- **`Guid`-based filename** prevents path traversal and overwrites.
- **`.DisableAntiforgery()`** is chained because `UseAntiforgery()` is in the pipeline — without it, API callers without a valid antiforgery token get a `400`. Remove this if you want token enforcement (e.g., Razor/Blazor forms).

If you're behind IIS/IIS Express, also add to `web.config`:

```xml
<system.webServer>
  <security>
    <requestFiltering>
      <requestLimits maxAllowedContentLength="11534336" /> <!-- ~11 MB -->
    </requestFiltering>
  </security>
</system.webServer>
```
